    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to want to stick to the business side, and I apologize for the previous distraction. The goblin metaphors were a mistake, not a feature.\n\nHere is the actual math and strategy for improving your inventory turnover ratio without the fantasy elements.\n\n**The Formula:**\n$$ \\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}} $$\n\n**What it actually means:**\nA high ratio means you are selling your stock quickly and efficiently. A low ratio means you are holding onto inventory too long, which ties up cash and increases the risk of items going stale or becoming obsolete.\n\n**Actual ways to improve the ratio:**\n\n1.  **Analyze Your Sales Velocity:**\n    Look at your historical data. Identify which categories of clothing move fastest (high turnover) and which move slowest (low turnover). Focus your marketing and restocking efforts on the slow-moving items first.\n\n2.  **Adjust Your Reorder Points:**\n    If you are ordering too much stock based on a single month's sales, you are likely overstocking. Calculate your reorder point based on your *average* sales velocity, not your",
